07438nam a22010335i 9789048550043DE-B159720210621102733.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||210621t20212021ne     fo  d z      eng d  a97890485500437 a10.1515/97890485500432doi  a(DE-B1597)576378  a(OCoLC)1243551336  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  anecNL 7aHIS0370202bisacsh04a28222300aMaking Truth in Early Modern Catholicism /ced. by Andreea Badea, Bruno Boute, Marco Cavarzere, Steven Broecke. 1aAmsterdam : bAmsterdam University Press, c[2021] 4c©2021  a1 online resource (336 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 aScientiae Studies ;v100tFrontmatter -- tTable of Contents -- tA Product's Glamour. Credibility, or the Manufacture and Administration of Truth in Early Modern Catholicism -- tPart I. Accommodating -- t1. Scholastic Approaches to Reasonable Disagreement -- t2. Regulating the Credibility of Non- Christians : Oaths on False Gods and Seventeenth-Century Casuistry -- t3. How to Be a Catholic Copernican in the Spanish Netherlands -- t4. Appearance and Essence : Speaking the Truth about the Body in the Early Modern Catholic Church -- tPart II. Performing -- t5. Saving Truth: Roman Censorship and Catholic Pluralization in the Confessionals of the Habsburg Netherlands, 1682-1686 -- t6. The Production of Truth in the Manufacture of Saints . Procedures, Credibility and Patronage in Early Modern Processes of Canonization -- t7. Credibility of the Past : Writing and Censoring History within Seventeenth-Century Catholicism -- t8. Heresy and Error in the Assessment of Modern Philosophical Psychology -- t9. Modern Philosophy and Ancient Heresies: New Wine in Old Bottles? -- tPart III. Embedding -- t10. "Experiences Are Not Successful Accompaniments to Knowledge of the Truth": The Trial of the Atheists in Late Seventeenth-Century Naples -- t11. Choosing Information, Selecting Truth : The Roman Congregations, the Benedictine Declaration, and the Establishment of Religious Plurality -- t12. Disciplining the Sciences in Conflict Zones : Pre-Classical Mechanics between the Sovereign State and the Reformed Catholic Religion -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aScholarship has come to value the uncertainties haunting early modern knowledge cultures; indeed, the awareness of the fragility and plurality of knowledge is now offered as a key element of "Baroque Science". Yet early modern actors never questioned the possibility of certainty itself; including the notion that truth is out there, universal, and therefore situated at one remove from human manipulations. This book addresses the central question of how early modern actors managed not to succumb to postmodern relativism, amidst uncertainties and blatant disagreements about the nature of God, Man, and the Universe. An international and interdisciplinary team of experts in fields ranging from Astronomy to Business Administration to Theology investigate a number of practices that are central to maintaining and functionalizing the notion of absolute truth, the certainty that could be achieved about it, and of the credibility of a wide plethora of actors in differentiating fields of knowledge.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 21. Jun 2021) 4aCultural Studies. 4aEarly Modern Period. 4aHistory. 4aPhilosophy. 4aTheology and Religion. 7aHISTORY / Renaissance.2bisacsh  aearly modern Catholicism.  aearly modern history.  ahistory of science.  aintellectual history.  areligious history.1 aBadea, Andreea, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBadea, Andreea, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aBoute, Bruno, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb